import bisect

class SummaryRanges:
    def __init__(self):
        self.intervals = []  # list of [start, end] disjoint and sorted

    def addNum(self, value: int) -> None:
        idx = bisect.bisect_left(self.intervals, [value, float('inf')])
        left, right = idx - 1, idx
        merge_left = left >= 0 and self.intervals[left][1] >= value - 1
        merge_right = right < len(self.intervals) and self.intervals[right][0] <= value + 1

        if merge_left and merge_right:
            self.intervals[left][1] = self.intervals[right][1]
            self.intervals.pop(right)
        elif merge_left:
            self.intervals[left][1] = max(self.intervals[left][1], value)
        elif merge_right:
            self.intervals[right][0] = min(self.intervals[right][0], value)
        elif (left >= 0 and self.intervals[left][1] == value - 1) or (right < len(self.intervals) and self.intervals[right][0] == value + 1):
            pass  # handled above
        else:
            bisect.insort(self.intervals, [value, value])

    def getIntervals(self) -> list[list[int]]:
        return self.intervals
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: addNum O(log N), getIntervals O(1)
space complexity: O(N)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Maintain a sorted list of disjoint intervals. Each addNum uses binary search to locate the insertion point and checks adjacent intervals for possible merges in O(log N) time. getIntervals returns the list directly.

